§14 — CURSOR-SPECIFIC INSTRUCTIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
When Operating as Cursor IDE
You are an AI-powered development assistant embedded in the Cursor editor.
Follow these additional guidelines:
Phase 0: Initialization
Before any code generation or audit work:

Load all six governing documents into context:

.cursorrules (this file)
aurafs.toml
compliance/PHYSICS_INVARIANTS.json
compliance/ALGORITHM_PROOFS.md
compliance/DARPA_TRL_VALIDATION.md
compliance/SECURITY_AUDIT.md


Build the module index by scanning src/ recursively
Resolve TRL-4 locks from aurafs.toml [modules.validated]
Verify physics::INVARIANTS module exists and loads from config

Phase 1: Physics Compliance Audit
Scan every .rs file for magic number violations:

Extract all numeric literals
Classify each as:

Physics constant (VIOLATION if not via INVARIANTS)
Standard constant (0, 1, 2, π, allowed)
False positive (buffer size, port number, etc.)


For violations, generate fix: replace with physics::INVARIANTS.<field>
For uncertain cases, add // TODO(PHYSICS_REVIEW): <reason>

Phase 2: Build Planning
Generate DEPLOYMENT_BUILD_PLAN.md with:

TRL-4 lock status table
Violation summary per subfolder
Estimated effort for compliance remediation
Dependency graph for build phases A–E
Risk assessment (e.g., Kyber-1024 integration complexity)

Code Generation Guidelines
When generating new Rust code:

Always use physics::INVARIANTS for constants
Always include doc comments for pub items
Always use Result<T, E> for fallible operations
Always use std::path::PathBuf for file paths
Prefer async functions with tokio for I/O
Avoid unsafe unless absolutely necessary
Check if file is TRL-4 locked before modifying public API

Error Handling
If you encounter a task you cannot complete:

Halt execution immediately
Report exact failure point (file path, line number)
Provide error message verbatim (don't paraphrase)
Suggest next steps for human intervention
Never fabricate fixes — be honest about limitations

